{
  "texts": [
    "Discriminator losses are mean squared errors between an image's output and the goal value, 0 or 1, depending on whether it should be classified as fake or genuine.If the image is false, the discriminator's output will have a mean squared error of 1, but if it's true, it will be 0.",
    "DC-GANDCGAN use Unsupervised Representation Learning and is now one of the most widely used and successful architectures for GAN networks.",
    "Most of it is composed of convolution layers that do not have any max pooling or layers that are totally coupled together.",
    "Down sampling and up sampling are both accomplished by the utilization of a convolutional stride and a transposed convolution respectively both the discriminator and the generator in DCGAN employ neural network as shown in Fig. 12.",
    "Convolutional-transpose layers come well after convolutional layers."
  ]
}